{% extends "_base.html.jinja" %}

{% block content %}
  {% with summary = {"title": "Cycle time", "headline": cycle_time.headline} %}
    {% include "_partials/metric_summary.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  {% with mode = 'detail', data = cycle_time %}
    {% include "_partials/cycle_time_tile.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  {% with data = work_items %}
    {% include "_partials/work_items_table.html.jinja" %}
  {% endwith %}

  <details class="detail-extras">
    <summary>Help · how to read, what to do next</summary>
    <h2>How to read this</h2>
    <p>
      Each point is one completed item plotted at its completion
      date (x) against its cycle time in days (y). Dashed lines
      are empirical percentiles of those cycle times: P50, P85,
      P95.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Cycle time is almost always right-skewed — commit on
        <strong>P85</strong>, not the mean.</li>
      <li>P85 rising while throughput holds steady = WIP is
        growing; rising P95 = process exceptions are piling up.</li>
      <li>Each long-tail outlier is a story worth tracing
        (rework, blocked dependencies, scope creep) — don't
        average them away.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Possible next steps</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Commit externally to <strong>P85</strong>; reserve P50
        for internal planning. If the gap is wide, fix variability
        before promising a date.</li>
      <li>Pick the most recent outlier and trace why it tailed.
        Almost always it's a queue or a handoff, not the work
        itself.</li>
      <li>Track P85 over time as the predictability KPI — a
        falling P85 with stable throughput is the canonical
        flow improvement signal.</li>
    </ul>
  </details>

  <a class="back-link" href="{{ ("/workflows/" ~ contract.name ~ "/") | keep_filters }}">← Back to dashboard</a>
{% endblock %}
